\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

CDM, large collapsed halos are 
\color black
replete
\color inherit
 with subhalos.
 Subhalos are distributed radially within their parent halos 
\color black
driven by several
\color inherit
 important dynamical processes.
 Segregation of subhalos is a phenomenon where subhalos with particular
 properties (such as mass at accretion) exhibit different radial profiles
 in their host halos.
 For example, subhalos with larger maximum circular velocity (i.e., having
 deeper potentials) tend to be closer to the center of their host halos
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wu_etal2013"

\end_inset

, while some studies found that more massive subhalos are internally less
 centrally concentrated 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "angulo_09,contini_11,de_lucia_04,reed05"

\end_inset

.
 In terms of dynamical friction, more massive subhalos (or the ones with
 larger maximum circular velocities) are expected to be closer to the center;
 however, they experience more tidal mass loss due to stronger tidal fields.
 It is hard to decouple those two competing effects, and this is why several
 studies find opposite trends in the radial distributions of subhalos.
 There are several studies showing that subhalos selected based on their
 masses at accretion and masses at the present time show different radial
 distributions: Subhalos selected by their masses at accretion show more
 centrally concentrated radial profiles than the ones selected by their
 present-day masses (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nagai05"

\end_inset

).
 Characterizing segregation is sensitive to the selection of the subhalos
 and their chosen properties.
 Ref.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

 investigated the segregation of dark matter subhalos in great detail using
 Spearman rank-order correlations to quantitatively evaluate the correlation
 between 12 different subhalo properties and segregation indicators (such
 as orbital energy and halo-centric radius).
 Ref.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

 found that accretion redshifts, which are the redshifts at which the subhalos
 are accreted by their host halos, is one of the key properties that determines
 segregation.
 Subhalos accreted earlier tend to have more centrally concentrated radial
 distributions than the ones accreted later.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is crucial to understand how a particular selection criterion for subhalos
 determines how they cluster differently on small scales.
 This is due to the fact that different radial profiles change 1-halo terms
 in correlation functions as well as 
\color black
small-scale redshift-space distortions.
 Those can possibly cause systematic errors/biases on large-scale measurements
\color inherit
 [
\color red
zentner,hearin_15
\color inherit
].
 In this chapter, we first investigate how the radial segregation of subhalos
 depends on their host halo masses.
 Then, we compute the observational signature of this effect using two-point
 correlation functions.
 Understanding segregation of the subhalos and comparing that to segregation
 of galaxies will provide the clues for the connection between halos and
 galaxies.
 These are of the main open questions in cosmology--how galaxies populate
 dark matter halos.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assembly history of host halos is essential to understanding the clustering.
 This dependence is known as an assembly bias, which is a phenomenon that
 the clustering of halos exhibits a dependence on additional properties
 beyond just their mass 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gao_etal05,wechsler06,gao_white07,li_etal08,hahn_etal09"

\end_inset

.
 In terms of the peak-background split formalism (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sheth_tormen99"

\end_inset

), the peaks of the same height in the initial density fluctuation collapse
 into halos of the same mass; however those peaks can be located in different
 environments (i.e., some peaks are in over-dense regions while others are
 in under-dense regions) and therefore have different assembly histories
 and therefore clustering 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dalal_etal08"

\end_inset

.
 These environmental differences result in the differences in the structural
 properties and internal structure of halos 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bullock01,wechsler02,hahn_etal07b,faltenbacher_white10"

\end_inset

.
 We revisit the manifestation of assembly history on the internal structure
 of the host halos regarding segregation.
 In particular, we explore whether segregation of the subhalos in their
 radial distributions shows some dependence on internal properties of host
 halos such as concentration, which are strongly correlated with their assembly
 history.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The outline of this paper is as follows.
 Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

2 summarizes the simulations we use in this work.
 Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3 presents our main results - mass dependence of segregation on radial profiles,
 its observational signature, and effects of assembly bias on segregation.
 Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

4 presents a discussion of these results and future work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the Bolshoi simulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bolshoi_11"

\end_inset

 which was run with the Adaptive Refinement Tree Code 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kravtsov_etal97,gottloeber_klypin08"

\end_inset

 assuming a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda{\rm CDM}$
\end_inset

 model with cosmological parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}=0.27$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.73$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{b}=0.0469$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{8}=0.82$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0.95$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0.70$
\end_inset

.
 The Bolshoi simulation used 
\begin_inset Formula $2048^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles in a 
\begin_inset Formula $250h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 box with a force resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm kpc}$
\end_inset

, yielding a particle mass of 
\begin_inset Formula $1.35\times10^{8}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 Dark matter halos and subhalos were identified using the 
\family typewriter
ROCKSTAR
\family default
 phase-space, temporal halo finder 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rockstar"

\end_inset

 and merger trees were constructed using the 
\family typewriter
CONSISTENT TREES 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rockstar_trees"

\end_inset


\family default
  procedures
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The catalogues used in this paper are publicly available at 
\begin_inset Flex Flex:URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://hipacc.ucsc.edu/Bolshoi/MergerTrees.html
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The results we present in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:correlation_fn"

\end_inset

 use the output of the simulation at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In what follows, we use the virial masses and maximum circular velocities
 (tagged 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\family typewriter
mvir
\family default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\family typewriter
vmax
\family default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) directly from the halo catalogues.
 The 
\family typewriter
ROCKSTAR
\family default
 halo finder computes halo masses based on spherical overdensities using
 a threshold of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{{\rm h}}=360$
\end_inset

.
 The halo mass and velocity functions start to show incompleteness at 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{10.4}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim200$
\end_inset

 particles) for the Bolshoi simulation.
 Below those masses, the halo mass distributions showed unphysical drop-offs
 indicating incomplete mass resolution.
 Therefore, we only select subhalos whose masses at accretion are greater
 than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{10.4}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mass Dependence of Segregation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we investigate the mass dependence of segregation by comparing
 the radial distribution of subhalos as a function of host halo mass.
 We select host halos in three mass bins: 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, and masses greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, for each sample, we split their corresponding subhalos based on their
 redshift of accretion 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $<0.1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1-0.25$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0.25-0.5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $>0.5$
\end_inset

.
 We chose 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0.25$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5$
\end_inset

 to further split samples, because the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.1$
\end_inset

 reach their first peri-center passage at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, while subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.25$
\end_inset

 have moved to their first apo-centric passage as noted in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

 (see Fig.7).
 We also split samples at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.5$
\end_inset

, because the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.5$
\end_inset

 will have completed their first 
\color black
full orbit
\color inherit
 and will have moved back towards the center.
 So, the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 are the ones which will have orbited inside their host halos several times.
 Using these subsamples, we compute the radial distances in units of their
 virial radius.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radial_massDependence"

\end_inset

 shows present radial profiles of subhalos as a function of the accretion
 redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 The solid lines are for subhalos in the host halos whose masses are greater
 than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, while circles and dashed lines correspond to the host halos whose masses
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}-10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}-10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 For the samples with the same accretion redshifts 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

, the radial profiles of the subhalos with different host halo masses do
 not exhibit any significant differences, which implies that segregation
 of subhalos is largely independent of host halo mass.
 Radial profiles with different accretion redshifts 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 tell us how subhalos move inside their host halos after accretion; most
 subhalos accreted after 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.1$
\end_inset

 are still close to the virial radius of their host halos, while the ones
 accreted around 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.1-0.25$
\end_inset

 have moved towards center.
 After going through their first peri-center passage, the subhalos have
 moved back towards their apo-centers, and this is why the subhalos accreted
 around 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.1-0.25$
\end_inset

 show more centrally concentrated radial profiles than the ones accreted
 around 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.25-0.5$
\end_inset

.
 The subhalos which are accreted earlier (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

) are closer to the center due to the inside-out assembly of dark matter
 halos (i.e., the virial radius of their host halos were smaller when those
 subhalos were accreted).
 This result is consistent with that reported in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

 (see Fig.
 7).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots_Cluster/radialDist_z_acc_massDependence.pdf
	width 70text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:radial_massDependence"

\end_inset

Radial profiles of subhalos as a function of the accretion redshifts 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 The solid lines are for the subhalos in the host halos whose masses are
 greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, while circles and dashed lines correspond to the host halos whose masses
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}-10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}-10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 The colors of each line represent the bin plotted as given in the legend.
 According to Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

, the subhalos accreted at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.1$
\end_inset

 reach their first peri-center and the ones accreted at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.25$
\end_inset

 are at their first peri-centric passage at present.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We further explore how subhalos move after accretion by computing their
 average halo-centric radius as a function of the accretion redshift as
 shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:halo_centric1"

\end_inset

.
 We first rank-order the subhalos based on their accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and split them into 30 equal number bins.
 Then, we compute the average halo-centric radius for each bin.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:halo_centric1"

\end_inset

 clearly tracks the radial motion of subhalos and does not show any mass-depende
nt feature for the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

.
 For the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

, their average halo-centric radius shows little indication of an orbit.
 This is probably due to major mergers and violent relaxation afterwards.
 Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

 predicted the halo-centric radius based on the adiabatic model; however,
 the prediction gave a smaller halo-centric radius for more massive host
 halos, while Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:halo_centric1"

\end_inset

 shows a weak opposite trend.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
