name "fig:halo_centric1"

\end_inset

The average halo-centric radius 
\begin_inset Formula $<r/R_{{\rm vir}}>$
\end_inset

 as a function of the accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 for the host halos with 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}>10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 (blue), 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13.5}-10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 (green), and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13}-10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 The blue dashed lines correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.25$
\end_inset

.
 All those lines show the almost same average halo-centric radii; however,
 for subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

, subhalos in larger host halos have slightly larger halo-centric radii
 than the ones in smaller halos.
 The difference between blue and red lines are about 
\begin_inset Formula $5\%$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the accretion redshift we use is the redshift that the subhalo
 is accreted most recently, but not all the subhalos stay inside of their
 host halos after accretion.
 There are some subhalos which move out from their host halos.
 Those halos are referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ejected halos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and including this transient population alters the clustering on small
 scales (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wetzel_etal13,sunayama16"

\end_inset

).
 Even though these ejected halos lie outside of the virial radius, they
 are likely to be gravitationally bound and accreted again.
 Some of the subhalos in the samples follow this sequence.
 So, we use the first accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

, which is the redshift that the subhalo is accreted for the first time,
 and repeat the same analysis done for Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radial_massDependence"

\end_inset

 and Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:halo_centric1"

\end_inset

.
 Here, we use the subhalos whose host halo masses are greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, but find that the same result holds for the subhalos with different host
 halo masses.
 The left panel of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:z_first"

\end_inset

 compares the average halo-centric radius as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

.
 They do not show any significant differences up to 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.4$
\end_inset

, while the average radius based on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

 is almost 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

 larger than the one for 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.4$
\end_inset

.
 For the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.4$
\end_inset

, we preferentially select subhalos which are more tightly bound to their
 host halos (because they never move out after accretion) and this is why
 the average radius is smaller for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 The right panel shows radial profiles of subhalos for 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}>0.5$
\end_inset

.
 By using the first accretion redshift, the radial distribution becomes
 less concentrated.
\end_layout

