\begin_layout Subsection
Correlation between 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we investigate the correlation between the accretion redshift
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and the retained mass and maximum circular velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}$
\end_inset

 are the subhalo mass/maximum circular velocity at the present time (in
 this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 are the subhalo mass/maximum circular velocity at accretion.
 The retained mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 measures the mass loss after subhalos are accreted by their host halos,
 and it is tightly correlated with the accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 due to tidal stripping.
 As a general trend, subhalos which are accreted earlier experience more
 mass loss because they stay in their host halos and, are subjected to dynamical
 processes for longer.
 The question is how well this property 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 correlates with the accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we have examined subhalos whose masses are greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:correlation"

\end_inset

 shows the median values of 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 to see the correlation between these quantities.
 The retained masses of the subhalos 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 are tightly correlated with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is expected, because the subhalos which are accreted earlier would
 be more stripped due to tidal effects and the amount of mass the subhalos
 lost and the time that the subhalos stay in their host halos should be
 correlated.
 Quantitatively, the cross correlation coefficient for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 is 0.651.
 We also check the correlation between 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

.
 As a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

, the change in halo mass is larger than the change in maximum circular
 velocity.
 However, this is because the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}\propto M_{{\rm vir}}^{1/3}$
\end_inset

 holds.
 Applying this scaling relation and converting 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

, the slope of 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 becomes almost the same as the slope for 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots_Cluster/scatter_z_massLoss3.pdf
	width 60text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:correlation"

\end_inset

Correlation between the accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and the retained mass of the subhalos 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 The line represents the median values of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log_{10}(m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}})}$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 The error bars represent one standard deviations.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radial_mass"

\end_inset

 shows the radial profiles of subhalos as a function of the retained mass
 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 for the host halos greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 We split the subhalo samples at 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}=10^{-0.36}$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 The radial profiles based on 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 (solid lines) are almost identical to the ones based on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 (dashed lines).
 This is due to the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 are correlated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots_Cluster/radialDist_z_acc_macc.pdf
	lyxscale 70
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:radial_mass"

\end_inset

Radial profiles of subhalos as a function of the retained mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 The solid lines are for the subhalos in the host halos whose masses are
 greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, while circles and dashed lines correspond to the host halos whose masses
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}-10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}-10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next question is whether the internal radial profiles of the subhalos
 show any extra dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 if the two samples have the same 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 dependence.
 To check this, we first compute the median 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}}(z_{{\rm acc}})$
\end_inset

.
 Then, we refer the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}>\overline{m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}}(z_{{\rm acc}})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

large-
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 subhalos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}<\overline{m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}}(z_{{\rm acc}})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small-
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 subhalos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This means that a subhalo's small- or large-
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 designation refers to whether its measured 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 value in the simulation is above- or below-average for its accretion redshift.
 Therefore, the two subsamples have almost identical distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 by construction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radial_zacc_mass"

\end_inset

 shows the radial profiles of the subhalos split into small/large-
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 subhalos as a function of the accretion redshift.
 We split the samples at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.5$
\end_inset

, as the trends suggest this natural split.
 The solid lines are for large-
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 subhalos, while the dashed lines are for small-
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 subhalos.
 The figure shows that the position and mass loss are tightly correlated
 for the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

; subhalos that lost more mass lie closer to the center as they are exposed
 to a stronger tidal field.
 On the other hand, subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 show almost no correlation between their radial profiles and mass loss.
 This is because those subhalos are accreted early enough so that their
 distribution is already
\color black
 virialized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots_Cluster/radialDist_z_acc_M14_2.pdf
	width 70text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:radial_zacc_mass"

\end_inset

 Radial profiles of subhalos as a function of the accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and the retained mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 We split the samples such that the samples which have the same cut in the
 accretion redshift have the same dependence on the accretion redshift.
 The detail about how we split the sample is in the text.
 For the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

, the position and mass loss are tightly correlated such that subhalos which
 lost more mass are closer to the center.
 On the other hand, subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 show no correlation between their radial profiles and mass losses.
 This is because those subhalos are accreted early enough that their distributio
n is already virialized (change the phrase).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Observational Signature: small-scale clusterings in real and redshift spaces
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:correlation_fn"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we investigate how segregation in the radial profiles appears
 observationally using two-point correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi(r)$
\end_inset

.
 
\color black
In real-space, we expect to see segregation of subhalos on the correlation
 functions similar to the radial profiles.
 The clustering of the subhalos accreted earlier has a larger amplitude
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $r<1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, which is about the size of the virial radius of the cluster-sized halos
 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}>10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{{\rm \odot}}}$
\end_inset

).
 However, the distance between a pair of the subhalos, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, is not normalized by the virial radius.
 So, we also expect the clustering of the subhalos on small scales depends
 on their host halo masses.
 In redshift-space, random motions of the subhalos within their host halos
 change the amplitude of the correlation functions.
 For the cluster-sized halos, a 1-halo term can be extended to 
\begin_inset Formula $10-15h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 due to large velocity dispersions and it is not clear how well we can see
 segregation of the subhalos on the redshift-space correlation functions.

\color red
 
\color inherit
However, small-scale redshift-space distortions have potential to test General
 Relativity and 
\color black
signpost
\color inherit
 theories of modified gravity.
 Several studies [
\color red
cite: zu et al.
\color inherit
] show that infall kinematics of clusters can differ by 
\begin_inset Formula $10-20\%$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $f(R)$
\end_inset

/Galileon modified gravity and General Relativity.
 Often modified gravity models provide larger velocity dispersions, which
 generates different scale-dependence on the redshift-space correlation
 functions on small scales.
 So, it is important to understand how particular selections of galaxies/subhalo
s alters the small-scale clustering in redshift-space, as this can be a
 potential source of systematic error in measurements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first select host halos whose masses are greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, and then look at the subsample the subhalos based on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 Unlike the radial profiles, we do not normalize the distances between the
 subhalos and the corresponding host halos by the virial radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 to compute correlation functions.
 So, using host halos with different mass ranges will change the clustering
 signals on small scales, but the generic trend of segregation remains the
 same.
 In all that follows, we will use 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{sub,sub}$
\end_inset

 to denote the auto-correlation of the subhalos and their host halos, and
 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{mm}$
\end_inset

 for the matter auto-correlation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first compute the correlation functions in real-space to see how well
 we can see the segregation on correlation functions without normalizing
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 and with 2-halo terms.
 The left panel of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:auto-sub_real"

\end_inset

 shows the auto-correlation functions of the subhalos split by 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 in real-space, and the right panel shows the ratio of the auto-correlation
 functions between the subhalos and matter.
 As expected, the clustering signal of those subhalos show different scale-depen
dence; the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 cluster more strongly than the ones with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $r>1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots_Cluster/Bolshoi_Mvir14_r.pdf
	lyxscale 70
	width 45text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots_Cluster/Bolshoi_Mvir14_r_ratio.pdf
	lyxscale 70
	width 45text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:auto-sub_real"

\end_inset

Left: Auto-correlation functions of subhalos in real-space as a function
 of the accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 Right: Subhalo auto-correlation functions divided by the matter auto-correlatio
n function.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we compute the correlation functions in redshift-space.
 The coordinates in redshift-space are defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{s}\equiv\vec{r}+\frac{v_{\parallel}}{H_{0}}\hat{r}_{\parallel},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{r}$
\end_inset

 is the position in real-space, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{r}_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

 is the line-of-sight component of the peculiar velocity and the unit vector
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{o}$
\end_inset

 is the Hubble constant.
 The peculiar velocity along the line-of-sight direction generates anisotropy
 in the density field and therefore angular dependence
\color red
 
\color black
in
\color inherit
 the correlation functions.
 Using the angle between a subhalo pair and the line-of-sight direction
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, we compute the 2D correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{s}(s,\mu)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\equiv cos\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Then, we project the 2D correlation functions onto Legendre polynomials
 to compute monopole and quadrupole terms such as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\xi_{s}^{(0)}(s)=(int)d\mu\xi_{s}(s,\mu)L_{0}(\mu),
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\xi_{s}^{(2)}(s)=(int)d\mu\xi_{s}(s,\mu)L_{2}(\mu),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{0}(\mu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}(\mu)$
\end_inset

 are the zeroth-order and second-order Legendre polynomials.
 The left panel of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:auto_sub-redshift"

\end_inset

 shows the monopole term of the subhalo auto-correlation functions, while
 the right panel shows the quadrupole terms.
 For the monopole terms, the segregation signal is completely smeared out
 and the correlation functions for each sample is almost indistinguishable;
 however, the quadrupole term shows different scale-dependence for each
 sample more clearly.
 This implies that these two subsamples of subhalos have different velocity
 dispersions on small scales (i.e., different Finger-of-God effect).
 To take a closer look at this, we first plot the correlation functions
 for various 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots_Cluster/Bolshoi_Mvir14_s_mono2.pdf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots_Cluster/Bolshoi_Mvir14_s_quad2.pdf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

