\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
And finally, we compare the subhalo velocity with respect to the velocity
 of their host halos for various values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:hist_vel"

\end_inset

.
 The figure shows that the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.25$
\end_inset

 have larger internal velocities than the ones with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.25$
\end_inset

.
 Quantitatively, the median value for the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.25$
\end_inset

 is about 
\begin_inset Formula $1000$
\end_inset

km/s, while it is about 
\begin_inset Formula $700$
\end_inset

km/s for the ones with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.25$
\end_inset

.
 This is likely because subhalos accreted earlier have lost much of their
 kinetic energy due to dynamical friction.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:hist_vel"

\end_inset

 is consistent with Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:xi_mu"

\end_inset

 in the sense that small internal velocities for subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

 will make the amplitude of the redshift-space correlation functions at
 the inner regions larger, because the pair-distances for those subhalos
 will not be elongated as much as for the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

.
 In addition to these comparions, we compute the velocity distribution of
 subhalos from the Halo Occupation Distribution (HOD).
 We first populate the host halos with 100 test subhalos each.
 Then, we assume that these subhalos are randomly moving inside the host
 halos.
 For this random motion, we draw from a Gaussian distribution with zero
 mean and variance given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle v_{x}^{2}\rangle=\langle v_{y}^{2}\rangle=\langle v_{z}^{2}\rangle=\frac{1}{3}\frac{GM_{{\rm vir}}}{R_{{\rm vir}}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 are the virial mass and virial radius of the host halos and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{y}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{z}$
\end_inset

 are the velocities of the satellite galaxies in each direction with respect
 to the velocity of the host halos.
 In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:hist_vel"

\end_inset

, we see that the HOD-predicted velocity distribution agrees well with the
 velocity distribution of the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.25$
\end_inset

.
 We find that the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.25$
\end_inset

 follow the virialized velocity distribution.
 For the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.25$
\end_inset

, their velocities will be under-estimated if the HOD model is used to compute
 their velocities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots_Cluster/velocity_z_acc.pdf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:hist_vel"

\end_inset

Histograms of the subhalos velocity with respect to the velocity of their
 host halos, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta v=|\vec{v}_{{\rm sub}}-\vec{v}_{{\rm host}}|$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{{\rm sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{{\rm host}}$
\end_inset

 are the velocity of the subhalo and their host halo respectively.
 The subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.25$
\end_inset

 have the median value (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim1000$
\end_inset

km/s), which is almost 
\begin_inset Formula $50\%$
\end_inset

 larger than the one with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.25$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim700$
\end_inset

km/s).
 This is consistent with the result shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:xi_mu"

\end_inset

 that the amplitude of the redshift-space correlation functions at 
\begin_inset Formula $s<1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 for the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 is larger than the one for 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

, which implies their pair-distances are not elongated as much as the one
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

.
 The blue dashed line is the predicted velocity distribution of subhalos
 from the HOD model.
 The detail of the HOD model is in the text.
 Note that the histograms are normalized by the total number of subhalos
 in each sample.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Effects of Assembly Bias on Segregation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we investigate whether the assembly history of the host
 halos affects the subhalo mass functions and spatial distribution of the
 subhalos.
 We first select the host halos whose masses are greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, but the same result still holds for different host halo masses
\color black
.
 Then, we split the sample based on their concentration.
 
\color inherit
We use the median concentration-mass relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}(M_{{\rm vir}})$
\end_inset

 shown in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dutton_maccio14"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\rm log}_{10}\bar{c}=-0.097{\rm log_{10}M_{vir}}+2.148.\label{eq:concen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For every halo in the Bolshoi catalogs, we use its tabulated 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}(M_{{\rm vir}}),$
\end_inset

 and then use the values 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}$
\end_inset

 to compare with the measured concentration for every halo.
 We will henceforth refer to halos with 
\begin_inset Formula $c<\bar{c}(M_{{\rm vir}})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low-concentration halos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and halos with 
\begin_inset Formula $c>\bar{c}(M_{{\rm vir}})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high-concentration halos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Again here, we now use concentrations as an indicator of assembly history:
 Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wechsler06"

\end_inset

 showed that early-forming halos tend to have higher concentration than
 late-forming halos.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the same sample of halos as before, we split subhalos based on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and compare their radial distributions as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radialDist_concen"

\end_inset

.
 The radial profiles of the subhalos do not exhibit any significant differences
 for different concentration of the host halos, which implies that segregation
 of subhalos is independent of assembly history.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:nfw"

\end_inset

 compares the radial distributions of the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 and the NFW profile 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nfw97"

\end_inset

 computed from the mean concentration for each sample.
 Even though the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 have more radially concentrated distributions, the NFW profiles are more
 radially concentrated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

