\begin_layout Section
Discussion/Future Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study, we investigated environmental effects on segregation of subhalos
 using the accretion redshift as a key parameter.
 We first studied whether the segregation of radial profiles show any dependence
 on the host halo mass.
 Then, we further explored whether the assembly history of host halos affects
 the radial distributions.
 In addition, we also computed two-point correlation functions for samples
 of subhalos (split by 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

) to examine expected observational signature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude this chapter with the following summary of our findings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Segregation of subhalos radially is independent of host halo mass.
 Until subhalos complete their firs
\color black
t orbit 
\color inherit
(i..e, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

), they track the radial motion of subhalos (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:halo_centric1"

\end_inset

).
 For the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

, their average halo-centric radius is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 due to major mergers and violent relaxation.
 Since the segregation is independent of the host halo mass, we can measure/comp
are this to galaxy segregation for clusters as well as groups.
 The generic trend is consistent with the findings in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.4$
\end_inset

, choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

 makes practically no difference in the radial distributions, while the
 average halo-centric radius based on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

 larger than the one using 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.4$
\end_inset

.
 In terms of galaxy formation, galaxy properties might be more correlated
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

, and comparing our finding to observations can be used to test which accretion
 redshift is more relevant to segregation on galaxy clustering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 are correlated, we test how much segregation actually comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 by generating samples 
\color red
with the same dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset


\color inherit
.
 For the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

, subhalos which lose more mass are preferentially closer to the center,
 while there is no correlation between the amount of mass loss and the radial
 distribution for the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We found that assembly history of host halos does not affect the radial
 distribution of subhalos, and the distribution of the subhalos does not
 agree with the NFW profile.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We found that the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 have almost twice as large an amplitude for the redshift-space correlation
 functions at the most inner region compared to that for the subhalos with
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

.
 This is because the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

 have almost 
\begin_inset Formula $50\%$
\end_inset

 larger internal velocity (i.e., the subhalo velocity with respect to the
 velocity of its host halo) than the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a possible direction for future work, we can compare segregation of radial
 profiles from simulations with observations using the age-matching technique,
 which connects the star formation rate of galaxies to the formation time
 of their dark matter halos (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hearin_etal13b"

\end_inset

).
 This will help us discern which galaxy property (such as color) might be
 correlated with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

.
 Also, we can extend our analysis of assembly bias using other parameters
 such as spin (which might be a good indicator of recent mergers).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[
\color red
discuss about comparing clustering of galaxies in clusters to clustering
 of field galaxies and connect to lensing
\color inherit
]
\end_layout

